#compdef arkflow
# =============================================================================
# arkflow — arkflow-rs/arkflow's HIGH-PERFORMANCE
#   RUST STREAM PROCESSING ENGINE — a single-
#   binary daemon that wires together pluggable
#   INPUT → PROCESSOR → OUTPUT pipelines over a
#   declarative YAML / TOML configuration.
#   Built on Apache Arrow + DataFusion for
#   columnar in-memory representation and SQL-
#   over-streams.  Modeled after Benthos /
#   Redpanda Connect but native Rust + Apache
#   Arrow throughout.  Direct dep on async-nats
#   v0.46 (the canonical Rust NATS client from
#   nats-io) for NATS JetStream / Core NATS
#   input + output transport.  Rust=103 leader
#   bump opening Axis 48.
#
# AXIS 48 — NATS MESSAGING CLIENT — OPENS @ R781
# =============================================
# Establishes a new three-language axis covering
# CLI tools written in language X that ship a
# DIRECT library binding to the NATS messaging
# protocol — the cloud-native pub/sub system
# from Synadia (formerly Apcera, now CNCF-
# incubated).  Per-language canonical
# implementations:
#   * Rust       : async-nats (this entry)
#                  — nats-io/nats.rs official
#                    Rust client, asynchronous,
#                    tokio-native, JetStream +
#                    KV + Object Store support
#                  — version 0.46 used here in
#                    `arkflow-plugin`
#                  — direct dep at
#                    `arkflow-rs/arkflow` crates/
#                    arkflow-plugin/Cargo.toml
#                    line: `async-nats = "0.46"`
#   * Go         : nats-io/nats.go (R782 will
#                  close)  — pure-Go, official,
#                  drop-in canonical client
#   * TS-Node    : nats.io/nats.js (R783 will
#                  close)  — pure-JS, official,
#                  with separate
#                  @nats-io/jetstream package
#
# NATS distinguishes from other corpus messaging
# axes (Kafka in Axis 47, MQTT-in-rumqttc) by:
#   - SUBJECT-BASED ROUTING — publishes go to
#     a dot-separated subject like `orders.us-
#     east.web`; subscribers wildcard with
#     `*` (single token) or `>` (all remaining
#     tokens).  No topic creation overhead;
#     subjects are ephemeral by default
#   - CORE NATS vs JETSTREAM — Core NATS is
#     fire-and-forget at-most-once.  JetStream
#     adds at-least-once / exactly-once
#     persistence + replay + KV store +
#     Object Store on top of the same wire
#     protocol.  arkflow's NATS input/output
#     supports both modes
#   - REQUEST-REPLY BUILT-IN — Core NATS
#     speaks request/reply natively via inbox
#     subjects.  No need for separate RPC
#     layer
#   - QUEUE GROUPS — multiple subscribers
#     sharing a queue-group name load-
#     balance.  Replaces Kafka consumer
#     groups for non-persistent workloads
#   - LEAF NODES + CLUSTERS + SUPERCLUSTERS —
#     NATS topology scales from single
#     server to multi-region supercluster
#     with no protocol changes
#
# Distinguishing arkflow itself from other
# corpus stream processors:
#   - VECTOR (`_vector`, vectordotdev/vector):
#     Vector is Rust + Apache Arrow + custom
#     VRL transformation language.  Vector
#     uses async-nats too BUT Vector's primary
#     niche is observability ingestion (logs/
#     metrics/traces).  arkflow's niche is
#     general stream processing with SQL-via-
#     DataFusion
#   - BENTHOS / REDPANDA CONNECT (`_benthos`,
#     `_connect`): Go-based, Bloblang
#     transformation language, similar input/
#     processor/output model.  arkflow is the
#     Rust analogue — same architectural model
#     but built on DataFusion + Arrow
#   - BENTO (`_bento`, warpstreamlabs/bento):
#     Fork of pre-license-change Benthos in
#     Go.  arkflow is the Rust-native
#     alternative
#   - APACHE FLINK / KAFKA STREAMS / KSQLDB:
#     JVM-hosted, heavy operationally.
#     arkflow is single-binary, lightweight,
#     no JVM
#   - RisingWave (`_risingwave`,
#     risingwavelabs/risingwave): also Rust,
#     also DataFusion-adjacent BUT
#     RisingWave is a STREAMING SQL DATABASE
#     with persistent state; arkflow is
#     stateless stream processing.  Different
#     target use-case
#
# arkflow plugin ecosystem (input + processor +
# output + buffer + codec stages, each pluggable
# via the `arkflow-plugin` crate):
#   * INPUT  STAGES         : NATS (async-nats),
#                             Kafka (rdkafka),
#                             MQTT (rumqttc),
#                             Redis (redis),
#                             HTTP (axum),
#                             file (tokio::fs),
#                             stdin, gRPC,
#                             Pulsar (pulsar),
#                             SQL (sqlx
#                             postgres + mysql)
#   * OUTPUT STAGES         : symmetric set —
#                             every input
#                             format also
#                             available as
#                             output
#   * PROCESSOR STAGES      : SQL (datafusion),
#                             JSON transform
#                             (datafusion-
#                             functions-json),
#                             protobuf encode/
#                             decode (prost-
#                             reflect), JMESPath
#                             query, rate-limit
#                             (governor), regex,
#                             custom Wasm
#   * BUFFER  STAGES        : in-memory,
#                             memory-mapped,
#                             disk-spool
#   * CODEC   STAGES        : JSON, MessagePack,
#                             Avro (Apache
#                             Arrow avro
#                             feature), Arrow
#                             IPC, raw bytes
#
# CONFIGURATION MODEL:
# A YAML file describes a list of named streams.
# Each stream has:
#   - exactly one  `input`     (source)
#   - zero or more `processor` (chained)
#   - zero or more `buffer`    (backpressure /
#                              disk spool)
#   - exactly one  `output`    (sink)
# Plus top-level `logging` (level, format=PLAIN|
# JSON, file_path) and optional `metrics`
# (Prometheus exposition on a configurable port).
#
# Example (NATS input → SQL transform → Kafka
# output):
#
#   logging:
#     level: info
#     format: PLAIN
#
#   streams:
#     - name: enrich-orders
#       input:
#         type: nats
#         url: nats://nats:4222
#         subject: orders.raw.*
#         queue_group: order-enrichers
#         jetstream: true
#         stream: ORDERS
#         consumer: enricher
#       processor:
#         - type: sql
#           query: |
#             SELECT
#               id, amount, currency,
#               UPPER(country)   AS country,
#               amount * 1.20    AS amount_eur
#             FROM input
#             WHERE amount > 0
#       output:
#         type: kafka
#         brokers: ["kafka:9094"]
#         topic: orders.enriched
#
# CRITICAL DIRECT DEPENDENCIES (from workspace
# Cargo.toml + crates/arkflow-plugin/Cargo.toml):
#   - async-nats 0.46          — NATS client
#                                [AXIS 48 LIBRARY]
#   - datafusion 47            — columnar query
#                                engine, SQL-on-
#                                streams
#   - datafusion-functions-json 0.47
#                              — JSON UDFs for
#                                DataFusion
#   - arrow-json 55            — Arrow ↔ JSON
#                                conversion
#   - prost-reflect 0.16       — protobuf
#                                reflection (for
#                                schema-aware
#                                protobuf
#                                codec)
#   - protobuf-parse 3.7       — .proto file
#                                parser
#   - reqwest 0.13             — HTTP client
#   - axum 0.8                 — HTTP server
#                                (HTTP input
#                                stage)
#   - clap 4.5                 — CLI parser
#   - tokio 1.x (full)         — async runtime
#   - sqlx 0.8                 — async SQL
#                                (postgres +
#                                mysql)
#   - governor 0.6             — rate-limiting
#                                processor
#   - prometheus 0.13          — metrics
#                                exposition
#   - serde + serde_yaml +     — config
#     toml                       parsing
#
# Rust 1.88+ MSRV per workspace.package
# `rust-version = "1.88"`.
#
# UPSTREAM:
#   * Source             : https://github.com/arkflow-rs/arkflow
#   * async-nats         : https://github.com/nats-io/nats.rs
#   * NATS docs          : https://docs.nats.io
#   * DataFusion         : https://datafusion.apache.org
#   * License            : Apache-2.0
#   * Maintainer         : chenquan <chenquan.dev@gmail.com>
#
# INSTALL:
#   # From source
#   cargo install --git https://github.com/arkflow-rs/arkflow arkflow
#
#   # Or clone + build
#   git clone https://github.com/arkflow-rs/arkflow
#   cd arkflow
#   cargo build --release -p arkflow
#   ./target/release/arkflow --help
#
# USAGE EXAMPLES:
#
#   # Run with a YAML config
#   arkflow -c streams.yaml
#   arkflow --config streams.yaml
#
#   # Validate config without starting engine
#   arkflow -c streams.yaml -v
#   arkflow --config streams.yaml --validate
#
#   # TOML config
#   arkflow -c streams.toml
#
#   # Print version
#   arkflow --version
#
#   # Help
#   arkflow --help
#
# OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/arkflow-rs/arkflow/blob/main/crates/arkflow-core/src/cli/mod.rs):
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)--version[show version]' \
    '(-c --config)'{-c+,--config=}'[path to the configuration file (YAML or TOML)]:config:_files -g "*.(yml|yaml|toml|json)"' \
    '(-v --validate)'{-v,--validate}'[only validate the config, do not start the engine]' \
    && ret=0

return ret
